column5: {36054: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36054",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects inbound HTTP traffic from an external network that matches patterns associated with the Ios.Backdoor.SYNful malware, which likely uses the HTTP protocol to communicate with its command and control server while blending in with legitimate traffic."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "36054", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic patterns that could indicate the use of a proxy or intermediary for command and control communications, which is a technique used by malware like Ios.Backdoor.SYNful to obscure the true source of the traffic."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {1280: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1280",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1046",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation"],\\n    "Explanation": "This Snort rule detects attempts to list services running on the portmapper (port 111), which is used to discover network services on Unix-based systems. column5: {1882: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1882",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1033",\\n    "Technique name": "System Owner/User Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to identify the primary user, currently logged in user, set of users that commonly uses a system, or whether a user is actively using the system"],\\n    "Explanation": "This Snort rule appears to be detecting attempts to retrieve user ID (uid) and group ID (gid) information, which could be used by an adversary to discover system owners or users on the compromised system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "1882", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1087",\\n    "Technique name": "Account Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of valid accounts, usernames, or email addresses on a system or within a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for traffic containing uid and gid values, which could indicate an attempt by an adversary to discover user accounts on the targeted system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {42255: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "42255",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1021",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use Valid Accounts to log into a service that accepts remote connections, such as telnet, SSH, and VNC"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to initiate a Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) session, which is a remote service used to access and control a system remotely. column5: {2044: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "2044",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1133",\\n    "Technique name": "External Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may leverage external-facing remote services to initially access and/or persist within a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to initiate a Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP) connection, which is a remote access protocol used to establish a virtual private network (VPN) connection over the Internet. Adversaries may leverage such external-facing remote services to gain initial access or maintain persistence within a network."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "2044", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "PPTP is a protocol that tunnels Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an IP network, allowing remote access to a private network. This rule may detect adversaries attempting to tunnel communications through PPTP to evade detection or access systems that would otherwise be unreachable."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {16207: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "16207",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1210",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation of Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit remote services to gain unauthorized access to internal systems once inside of a network."],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a buffer overflow vulnerability in the MIT Kerberos V5 KAdminD klog_vsyslog server, which is a remote service. column5: {34709: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1499",\\n    "Technique name": "Endpoint Denial of Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may perform Endpoint Denial of Service (DoS) attacks to degrade or block the availability of services to users"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to perform a denial of service attack against the Kerberos authentication service, which is a type of Endpoint Denial of Service attack aimed at disrupting the availability of the service to legitimate users."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "34709", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1558",\\n    "Technique name": "Steal or Forge Kerberos Tickets",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to subvert Kerberos authentication by stealing or forging Kerberos tickets to enable Pass the Ticket"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule is primarily focused on detecting a denial of service attempt, it is also relevant to the technique of stealing or forging Kerberos tickets, as an adversary may attempt to exploit vulnerabilities in the Kerberos protocol to gain unauthorized access or elevate privileges."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44474: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44474",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1573",\\n    "Technique name": "Encrypted Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects malware (GHBkdr) attempting to spoof the TLS Change Cipher message, which is part of the TLS handshake process used to establish an encrypted channel for communication. The rule looks for specific byte patterns associated with this malware\\\'s attempt to create an encrypted channel for command and control communication."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44474", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect the GHBkdr malware spoofing a legitimate TLS Change Cipher message, which is an attempt to masquerade the malicious traffic as benign encrypted communication to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47844: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47844",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a variant of the Win.Downloader.DDECmdExec malware, which downloads and executes malicious payloads from an external source, aligning with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47844", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1059",\\n    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for specific patterns related to executing commands using the Windows command interpreter (cmd.exe), which is consistent with the Command and Scripting Interpreter technique."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {47848: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47848",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1218",\\n    "Technique name": "System Binary Proxy Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may bypass process and/or signature-based defenses by proxying execution of malicious content with signed, or otherwise trusted, binaries"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a variant of the Win.Downloader.DDECmdExec malware, which uses the trusted Windows system binary \\\'msiexec.exe\\\' to proxy execution of malicious code, likely to bypass security controls."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47848", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for network traffic related to downloading a malicious file, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique where tools or files are transferred to a compromised system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48402: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48402",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from an infected host, which could be an attempt by the Emotet malware to communicate with its command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP. column5: {50096: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50096",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the download of the Responder tool, which is used for performing AiTM attacks by poisoning the victim\\\'s network to redirect traffic through the attacker\\\'s system, enabling behaviors like credential theft."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50464: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1135",\\n    "Technique name": "Network Share Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may look for folders and drives shared on remote systems as a means of identifying sources of information to gather as a precursor for Collection and to identify potential systems of interest for Lateral Movement\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to enumerate network shares on systems via the NetBIOS Session Service (port 445), which is commonly used for lateral movement and discovery of sensitive data on remote systems."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50464", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1018",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote System Discovery",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of other systems by IP address, hostname, or other logical identifier on a network that may be used for Lateral Movement from the current system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for activity related to the Responder tool, which can be used to discover and enumerate systems on the network, enabling lateral movement."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {57756: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "57756",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1568",\\n    "Technique name": "Dynamic Resolution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may dynamically establish connections to command and control infrastructure to evade common detections and remediations"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to use DNS Fast Flux, a technique used by malware to rapidly and randomly change the IP addresses associated with a domain name, making it harder to block or take down the malicious infrastructure.
